20of%20what's%20happening%20to%20families%20trapped%20inside%20the%20conflict.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A96%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews.sky.com%2Fstory%2Frachel-riley-condemns-hideous-and-unthinkable-israel-hamas-war-12985744%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews-sky-com.cdn.ampproject.org%2Fc%2Fs%2Fnews.sky.com%2Fstory%2Famp%2Frachel-riley-condemns-hideous-and-unthinkable-israel-hamas-war-12985744%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews.sky.com%2Fstory%2Famp%2Frachel-riley-condemns-hideous-and-unthinkable-israel-hamas-war-12985744%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22SC%20Rejects%20Married%20Woman's%20Plea%20to%20Abort%2027-Week%20Pregnancy%2C%20Upholds%20MTP%20Act%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cimg%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2021%2F09%2F08152223%2Ffreestocks-ux53SGpRAHU-unsplash.jpg%5C%22%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3ENew%20Delhi%3A%3C%2Fstrong%3E%20At%20last%2C%20Chief%20Justice%20of%20India%20(CJI)%20D.Y.%20Chandrachud-led%20three-judge%20Bench%20of%20the%20Supreme%20Court%20found%20merit%20in%20the%20opinion%20submitted%20by%20the%20Medical%20Board%20of%20the%20All%20India%20Institute%20of%20Medical%20Sciences%20(AIIMS)%20about%20the%20viability%20of%20the%2026-week%20old%20pregnancy%20of%20the%20married%20mother%20who%20is%20the%20petitioner%20before%20the%20court%2C%20and%20the%20impact%20of%20her%20postpartum%20psychosis%20on%20the%20child%20as%20well%20as%20on%20her%2C%20if%20she%20continued%20her%20pregnancy%20to%20full-term.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20Bench%20dismissed%20the%20plea%20of%20the%20married%20petitioner%20to%20terminate%20her%20pregnancy%20in%20the%2027th%20week%2C%20on%20the%20basis%20of%20the%20report%20of%20the%20Board%20which%20ruled%20out%20any%20adverse%20impact%20of%20her%20mental%20condition%20on%20the%20child%20as%20well%20as%20on%20her%20if%20she%20carried%20the%20pregnancy%20to%20its%20full%20term.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20Bench%2C%20also%20comprising%20Justice%20J.B.%20Pardiwala%20and%20Justice%20Manoj%20Misra%2C%20had%20directed%20the%20Board%20to%20submit%20a%20report%20after%20a%20fresh%20appraisal%20of%20her%20pregnancy%20as%20well%20as%20her%20mental%20health%2C%20following%20the%20doubts%20arising%20from%20her%20prescriptions%20in%20connection%20with%20her%20treatment%20for%20depression%20after%20the%20delivery%20of%20her%20second%20child.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20pregnant%20petitioner%20had%20claimed%20that%20she%20has%20been%20undergoing%20treatment%20for%20postpartum%20psychosis%20since%20October%2010%2C%202022.%20She%20got%20married%20on%20December%203%2C%202017.%20While%20the%20first%20child%20was%20born%20on%20September%2030%2C%202019%2C%20the%20second%20was%20born%20on%20September%2030%2C%202022.%20As%20the%20prescriptions%20for%20her%20treatment%20for%20postpartum%20psychosis%20do%20not%20specify%20the%20nature%20of%20the%20ailment%20for%20which%20drugs%20were%20reportedly%20prescribed%2C%20the%20Bench%20had%20requested%20the%20Board%20to%20review%20the%20same%20and%20revert.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20Board%2C%20in%20its%20second%20report%2C%20submitted%20that%20the%20fetus%20is%20not%20suffering%20from%20any%20abnormality%20at%20all%2C%20let%20alone%20any%20%E2%80%98substantial%E2%80%99%20abnormality%2C%20as%20provided%20by%20subsection%202(b)%20of%20Section%203%20of%20the%20Medical%20Termination%20of%20Pregnancy%20Act%2C%201971%20(MTP%20Act).%20In%20the%20first%20report%2C%20the%20Board%20had%20merely%20mentioned%20that%20the%20fetus%20is%20normal%2C%20and%20the%20pregnancy%20is%20viable.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ESecondly%2C%20the%20Board%20informed%20the%20court%20that%20the%20continuance%20of%20the%20pregnancy%20of%20the%20petitioner%20to%20full%20term%20would%20not%20be%20jeopardised%20by%20the%20drugs%20which%20may%20be%20prescribed%20for%20the%20postpartum%20psychosis%2C%20from%20which%20she%20is%20suffering.%20The%20Board%20was%20clearly%20of%20the%20view%20that%20the%20medicines%20for%20the%20ailment%20that%20the%20petitioner%20had%20been%20taking%20earlier%20had%20not%20affected%20the%20child.%20The%20Board%20also%20offered%20to%20recommend%20alternative%20medication%20for%20the%20same%20going%20forward%20so%20as%20to%20neither%20jeopardise%20the%20well-being%20of%20the%20petitioner%20nor%20the%20fetus%20in%20that%20regard.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EWhen%20the%20petitioner%E2%80%99s%20counsel%2C%20Dr.%20Amit%20Mishra%20pointed%20out%20that%20ultrasound%20scans%20can%E2%80%99t%20detect%20all%20abnormalities%20of%20the%20fetus%2C%20the%20CJI%20replied%20saying%20any%20invasive%20tests%20at%20this%20stage%20are%20not%20in%20the%20interest%20of%20the%20petitioner.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EMishra%20then%20sought%20to%20submit%20that%20the%20life%20of%20the%20pregnant%20married%20woman%20cannot%20be%20treated%20differently%20from%20that%20of%20an%20unmarried%20woman%20or%20a%20rape%20survivor.%20His%20argument%20was%20that%20since%20the%20court%20had%20earlier%20permitted%20abortion%20in%20the%20case%20of%20the%20latter%20even%20after%2026%20weeks%20on%20the%20grounds%20of%20the%20mental%20health%20of%20the%20mother%2C%20the%20same%20should%20be%20permissible%20in%20the%20case%20of%20the%20former.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2062vw%2C%20840px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2020%2F05%2F18171021%2Fpregnant-woman-under-cloudy-sky-in-silhouette-photography-1717292.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%221200%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2020%2F05%2F18171021%2Fpregnant-woman-under-cloudy-sky-in-silhouette-photography-1717292.jpg%201200w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2020%2F05%2F18171021%2Fpregnant-woman-under-cloudy-sky-in-silhouette-photography-1717292-300x182.jpg%20300w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2020%2F05%2F18171021%2Fpregnant-woman-under-cloudy-sky-in-silhouette-photography-1717292-1024x621.jpg%201024w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-455303%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22728%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EPhoto%3A%20Marcos%20Flores%2FPexels%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20CJI%2C%20however%2C%20responded%20that%20the%20court%20sought%20to%20end%20the%20discrimination%20against%20unmarried%20mothers%20who%20might%20want%20to%20end%20their%20pregnancies%20on%20legitimate%20grounds.%20In%20this%20case%2C%20however%2C%20the%20question%20of%20any%20harm%20to%20the%20petitioner%E2%80%99s%20mental%20health%20has%20been%20ruled%20out%20by%20the%20Medical%20Board.%20%E2%80%9CThis%20argument%20does%20not%20help%20your%20client%2C%E2%80%9D%20the%20CJI%20told%20Mishra.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20CJI%20was%20of%20the%20view%20that%20if%20interpreted%20broadly%2C%20the%20pro-choice%20provisions%20of%20the%20MTP%20Act%20would%20defeat%20its%20very%20purpose.%20%E2%80%9CIf%20the%20risk%20to%20the%20mother%E2%80%99s%20life%20is%20to%20be%20interpreted%20as%20a%20risk%20to%20a%20%E2%80%98meaningful%20life%E2%80%99%2C%20can%20we%20permit%20termination%20even%20in%20the%2035th%20week%3F%E2%80%9D%20the%20CJI%20asked.%C2%A0%20This%20was%20in%20response%20to%20Mishra%E2%80%99s%20contention%20that%20the%20petitioner%20is%20in%20no%20position%20to%20rear%20the%20third%20child%2C%20even%20if%20it%20is%20viable%2C%20in%20view%20of%20her%20family%E2%80%99s%20financial%20position%20and%20her%20mental%20health.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20additional%20solicitor%20general%2C%20Aishwarya%20Bhati%2C%20told%20the%20Bench%20that%20the%20question%20before%20the%20court%20is%20not%20a%20case%20of%20pro-choice%20versus%20pro-life.%20Instead%2C%20it%20should%20be%20interpreted%20as%20pre-term%20delivery%20versus%20normal%20delivery%2C%20as%20the%20latter%20would%20give%20the%20child%20%E2%80%9Ca%20fighting%20chance%E2%80%9D%20to%20survive.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EShe%20cited%20instances%20of%20doctors%20performing%20abortions%20during%2020-24%20weeks%20of%20pregnancy%2C%20when%20they%20heard%20cries%20of%20the%20fetuses%20and%20when%20they%20had%20to%20stop%20their%20heartbeats.%20According%20to%20her%2C%20the%20mother%20does%20not%20have%20a%20choice%20for%20abortion%2C%20if%20the%20pregnancy%20crosses%2024%20weeks%2C%20and%20if%20the%20child%20is%20found%20viable%20by%20the%20doctors.%20%E2%80%9CPre-term%20delivery%20should%20be%20rarest%20of%20rare%2C%E2%80%9D%20she%20told%20the%20Bench.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20Bench%20also%20heard%20senior%20advocate%20Colin%20Gonsalves%2C%20who%20volunteered%20to%20make%20submissions.%C2%A0%20He%20claimed%20that%20the%20right%20of%20the%20woman%2C%20under%20contemporary%20international%20law%2C%20is%20absolute%2C%20as%20far%20as%20the%20decision%20to%20abort%20is%20concerned.%20%E2%80%9CThere%20is%20no%20right%20of%20an%20unborn%20child%20until%20it%20is%20separated%20from%20the%20womb%2C%E2%80%9D%20he%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EGonsalves%20claimed%20that%20the%20Union%20of%20India%20had%20laid%20down%20guidelines%20to%20be%20followed%20in%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.reproductiverights.org%2Fsites%2Fcrr.civicactions.net%2Ffiles%2Fdocuments%2FDatar_v_India.pdf%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3ENikhil%20Datar%3C%2Fem%3E%20case%3C%2Fa%3E%20for%20late-term%20pregnancies%2C%20and%20they%20are%20relevant%20in%20this%20case.%20The%20CJI%20asked%20Gonsalves%20to%20tell%20parliament%20if%20he%20thinks%20the%20international%20law%20has%20changed%20over%20the%20years%20in%20favour%20of%20the%20absolute%20right%20of%20choice%20for%20the%20mother.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EAfter%20briefly%20listening%20to%20Gonsalves%2C%20the%20CJI%20requested%20him%20to%20%E2%80%9Ckeep%20his%20powder%20dry%E2%80%9D%2C%20as%20his%20arguments%20are%20relevant%20in%20a%20challenge%20to%20the%20law%20and%20not%20in%20this%20case.%20%E2%80%9CWe%20have%20to%20apply%20the%20law%20as%20it%20stands%2C%E2%80%9D%20the%20CJI%20made%20it%20clear%2C%20adding%20that%20the%20Union%20of%20India%E2%80%99s%20guidelines%20in%20the%20Nikhil%20Datar%20case%20cannot%20override%20the%20law.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20CJI%20told%20Gonsalves%20that%20it%20is%20not%20as%20if%20India%20is%20regressive%2C%20as%20even%20in%20the%20US%20the%20landmark%20%3Cem%3ERoe%20vs%20Wade%3C%2Fem%3E%20(which%20had%20recognised%20the%20right%20to%20abortion)%20has%20been%20diluted.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EGonsalves%20then%20cautioned%20the%20Bench%20that%20if%20abortion%20can%E2%80%99t%20be%20carried%20out%2C%20no%20abortion%20can%20take%20place%20even%20before%2024%20weeks%20of%20pregnancy%2C%20and%20the%20Bench%20may%20be%20setting%20a%20wrong%20precedent%20in%20this%20case.%C2%A0%20He%20added%20that%20universally%20the%20gestational%20standards%20have%20become%20obsolete%2C%20and%20cited%20the%20World%20Health%20Organisation%E2%80%99s%20(WHO%E2%80%99s)%20norms%20to%20support%20his%20claim.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20CJI%20asked%20him%20whether%20the%20Bench%20could%20override%20the%20statute%20because%20of%20what%20the%20WHO%20had%20laid%20down.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EMishra%20then%20told%20the%20Bench%20that%20the%20petitioner%20had%20clearly%20ruled%20out%20continuance%20of%20her%20pregnancy%20for%20three%20more%20months%20as%20not%20possible.%20The%20CJI%20noted%20that%20the%20Bench%20is%20aware%20that%20her%20pregnancy%20was%20accidental%20and%20unplanned.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EBhati%20submitted%20to%20the%20bench%20that%20the%20Union%20government%20is%20prepared%20to%20meet%20the%20costs%20of%20her%20treatment%20at%20AIIMS%20till%20her%20full%20term%20of%20pregnancy%20is%20over%2C%20and%20also%20accept%20the%20responsibility%20of%20giving%20the%20child%20in%20adoption%20if%20she%20is%20willing.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EThe%20split%20verdict%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3Cstrong%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20three-judge%20Bench%E2%80%99s%20decision%20follows%20a%20split%20decision%20by%20a%20division%20Bench%20comprising%20Justice%20Hima%20Kohli%20and%20Justice%20B.V.%20Nagarathna.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EJustice%20Hima%20Kohli%20relied%20on%20the%20email%20sent%20by%20one%20of%20the%20members%20of%20the%20AIIMS%20Medical%20Board%20to%20Bhati%2C%20which%20clearly%20said%20that%20the%20baby%20was%20viable%2C%20showed%20signs%20of%20life%2C%20and%20had%20a%20strong%20possibility%20of%20survival.%20Feticide%20(stopping%20the%20fetal%20heart)%20can%20be%20done%20before%20termination%2C%20only%20with%20a%20directive%20from%20the%20court%2C%20the%20doctor%20had%20said.%20Feticide%20is%20done%20for%20a%20fetus%20which%20has%20abnormal%20development%2C%20but%20generally%20not%20done%20in%20a%20normal%20fetus%2C%20she%20added.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%3Cins%3EAlso%20read%3A%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fgovernment%2Fcentre-seeks-recall-of-scs-order-permitting-married-woman-to-terminate-26-week-pregnancy%5C%22%3ECentre%20Seeks%20Recall%20of%20SC%E2%80%99s%20Order%C2%A0Permitting%20Married%20Woman%20To%20Terminate%2026-Week%20Pregnancy%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fins%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIf%20feticide%20is%20not%20performed%2C%20this%20is%20not%20a%20termination%2C%20but%20a%20pre-term%20delivery%20where%20the%20baby%20born%20will%20be%20provided%20treatment%20and%20care.%C2%A0%20A%20baby%20who%20is%20born%20preterm%20and%20also%20of%20such%20low%20birth%20weight%20will%20have%20a%20long%20stay%20in%20the%20intensive%20care%20unit%2C%20with%20a%20high%20possibility%20of%20immediate%20and%20long%20term%20physical%20and%20mental%20disability%20which%20will%20seriously%20jeopardise%20the%20quality%20of%20life%20of%20the%20child.%20In%20such%20a%20scenario%2C%20the%20doctor%20wanted%20to%20know%20what%20was%20to%20be%20done%20with%20the%20baby.%20If%20the%20parents%20agree%20to%20keep%20the%20child%2C%20this%20will%20take%20a%20major%20physical%2C%20mental%2C%20emotional%2C%20and%20financial%20toll%20on%20the%20couple.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIf%20it%20is%20to%20go%20for%20adoption%2C%20the%20process%20needs%20to%20be%20spelt%20out%20clearly%20so%20that%20a%20baby%20who%20comes%20into%20the%20world%20will%20have%20a%20better%20chance%20at%20life%20if%20the%20delivery%20happens%20after%20at%20least%20eight%20weeks%20(that%20is%20beyond%2026%20weeks%2C%20when%20the%20doctor%20sent%20the%20email%20to%20Bhati).%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EJustice%20Kohli%20considered%20this%20email%20sent%20to%20Bhati%20on%20October%2010%2C%20as%20a%20dissenting%20view%20by%20a%20member%20of%20the%20Board%2C%20because%20of%20which%20her%20judicial%20conscience%20did%20not%20permit%20the%20petitioner%20to%20terminate%20her%20pregnancy.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EOn%20October%209%2C%20Justice%20Kohli%20joined%20Justice%20Nagarathna%20in%20permitting%20the%20termination%20of%20pregnancy%20after%20considering%20the%20medical%20report%20of%20the%20Board%20submitted%20on%20October%206.%20The%20Board%20had%20opined%20that%20the%20chances%20of%20postpartum%20psychosis%20were%20present%20even%20at%20this%20gestation%20following%20delivery.%20The%20Board%20was%20of%20the%20view%20that%20the%20chances%20of%20complications%20due%20to%20hysterectomy%20were%20there%20at%20this%20gestation.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%20even%20before%20the%20detailed%20order%20had%20been%20uploaded%2C%20a%20mention%20was%20made%20for%20seeking%20recall%20of%20the%20order%20before%20the%20CJI%20by%20Bhati%20and%20the%20directions%20issued%20by%20the%20Kohli-Nagarathna%20Bench%20to%20the%20doctors%20at%20AIIMS%20to%20terminate%20pregnancy%20remained%20unimplemented.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIn%20her%20dissenting%20order%2C%20Justice%20Nagarathna%20noted%20the%20strong%20determination%20of%20the%20petitioner-mother%20to%20medically%20terminate%20her%20pregnancy%20and%20to%20also%20not%20keep%20the%20baby%20even%20if%20it%20survives.%20The%20petitioner%E2%80%99s%20submission%20on%20an%20affidavit%20that%20the%20government%20can%20take%20care%20of%20the%20baby%20in%20case%20it%20survives%20and%20even%20can%20give%20it%20in%20adoption%2C%20or%20whatever%20is%20deemed%20suitable%20to%20them%2C%20was%20noted%20by%20Justice%20Nagarathna.%20The%20petitioner%20had%20also%20declared%20that%20she%20would%20have%20no%20objection%20or%20any%20claim%20over%20the%20baby%20in%20the%20future%20and%20that%20she%20had%20taken%20the%20decision%20out%20of%20her%20own%20free%20will%2C%20choice%20and%20without%20pressure%20from%20anyone%2C%20after%20having%20understood%20all%20facts%20and%20surrounding%20circumstances%20about%20her%20case.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EJustice%20Nagarathna%20concluded%20that%20the%20petitioner%E2%80%99s%20decision%20must%20be%20respected%20and%20the%20interest%20of%20the%20mother%20of%20two%20children%20and%20expecting%20the%20third%20in%20a%20year%E2%80%99s%20time%20from%20giving%20birth%20to%20the%20second%20child%20had%20to%20be%20given%20preference.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20socioeconomic%20condition%20in%20which%20the%20petitioner%20is%20placed%2C%20the%20fact%20that%20she%20has%20already%20two%20children%2C%20the%20second%20child%20being%20only%20one%20year%20of%20age%20and%20the%20fact%20that%20she%20reiterated%20that%20her%20delicate%20mental%20condition%20and%20health%20and%20the%20medicines%20that%20she%20has%20been%20taking%20for%20the%20same%2C%20do%20not%20support%20her%20to%20continue%20with%20her%20pregnancy%20must%20be%20considered%20by%20the%20court.%20Courts%20cannot%20substitute%20their%20view%20in%20the%20matter%20with%20that%20of%20the%20decision%20of%20the%20petitioner.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EInterestingly%2C%20Justice%20Nagarathna%20relied%20on%20the%20CJI%E2%80%99s%20verdict%20in%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Findiankanoon.org%2Fdoc%2F134729746%2F%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3EX%20vs%20Health%20%26amp%3B%20Family%20Welfare%20Department%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%20(2022).%C2%A0%20The%20CJI%20had%20held%20in%20this%20case%20that%20the%20decision%20to%20have%20or%20not%20to%20have%20an%20abortion%20is%20borne%20out%20of%20complicated%20life%20circumstances%2C%20which%20only%20the%20woman%20can%20choose%20on%20her%20own%20terms%20without%20external%20interference%20or%20influence.%20Reproductive%20autonomy%20requires%20that%20every%20pregnant%20woman%20has%20the%20intrinsic%20right%20to%20choose%20to%20undergo%20or%20not%20to%20undergo%20an%20abortion%20without%20any%20consent%20or%20authorisation%20from%20a%20third%20party%2C%20the%20CJI%20held%20in%20this%20case.%20The%20consequences%20of%20an%20unwanted%20pregnancy%20on%20a%20woman%E2%80%99s%20body%20as%20well%20as%20her%20mind%20cannot%20be%20understated%2C%20the%20CJI%20had%20added.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EJustice%20Nagarathna%20had%20underlined%20this%20sentence%20in%20CJI%E2%80%99s%20verdict%20in%20%3Cem%3EX%20vs%20Health%20%26amp%3B%20Family%20Welfare%20Department%3C%2Fem%3E%3A%20%E2%80%9CThe%20decision%20to%20carry%20the%20pregnancy%20to%20its%20full%20term%20or%20terminate%20it%20is%20firmly%20rooted%20in%20the%20right%20to%20bodily%20autonomy%20and%20decisional%20autonomy%20of%20the%20pregnant%20woman.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EJustice%20Nagarathna%20also%20held%20that%20in%20unwanted%20pregnancies%20as%20in%20the%20present%20case%2C%20whether%20the%20child%20to%20be%20born%20is%20viable%20or%20if%20the%20child%20would%20be%20a%20healthy%20child%20are%20not%20relevant%20considerations.%C2%A0%20What%20is%20to%20be%20focussed%20upon%20is%20whether%20the%20pregnant%20lady%20intends%20to%20give%20birth%20to%20a%20child%20or%20not%20%E2%80%93%20this%20is%20what%20has%20been%20emphasised%20by%20the%20court%20in%20%3Cem%3EX%20vs%20Health%20%26amp%3B%20Family%20Welfare%20Department%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20Justice%20Nagarathna%20noted%20in%20her%20separate%20order%20of%20split%20judgment.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EJustice%20Nagarathna%20also%20found%20it%20incongruous%20to%20conclude%20that%20the%20fetus%20has%20a%20separate%20identity%20from%20the%20mother.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIt%20could%20be%20said%2C%20however%2C%20that%20the%20current%20three-judge%20Bench%20on%20Monday%20had%20taken%20care%20to%20ensure%20that%20the%20petitioner%E2%80%99s%20physical%20and%20mental%20health%20would%20not%20suffer%20as%20a%20result%20of%20her%20continuing%20the%20pregnancy.%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1697474869000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2021%2F09%2F08152223%2Ffreestocks-ux53SGpRAHU-unsplash.jpg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Flaw%2Fsc-rejects-married-womans-plea-to-abort-27-week-pregnancy-upholds-mtp-act%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22The%20court%20said%20it%20found%20merit%20in%20the%20opinion%20submitted%20by%20the%20Medical%20Board%20of%20the%20All%20India%20Institute%20of%20Medical%20Sciences%20(AIIMS)%2C%20which%20stated%20that%20the%20fetus%20is%20not%20suffering%20from%20any%20abnormality%20as%20mentioned%20in%20the%20Medical%20Termination%20of%20Pregnancy%20Act.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A1%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Flaw%2Fsc-rejects-married-womans-plea-to-abort-27-week-pregnancy-upholds-mtp-act%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Diana%20and%20Dodi%20Fayed%20seen%20in%20first-look%20images%20of%20The%20Crown's%20final%20series%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%22%2C%22published%22%3A1697471160000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fe3.365dm.com%2F23%2F10%2F768x432%2Fskynews-elizabeth-debicki-princess-diana_6323525.jpg%3F20231016172308%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews.sky.com%2Fstory%2Fthe-crown-princess-diana-and-dodi-fayed-seen-in-first-look-images-of-final-series-12985703%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22Princess%20Diana's%20relationship%20with%20Dodi%20Fayed%20is%20among%20the%20storylines%20teased%20in%20the%20first%20images%20released%20of%20the%20final%20series%20of%20The%20Crown.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A45%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews.sky.com%2Fstory%2Fthe-crown-princess-diana-and-dodi-fayed-seen-in-first-look-images-of-final-series-12985703%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22'We%2